{"parse":{"title":"Medism","pageid":1126261,"revid":732754188,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Greece\" title=\"Ancient Greece\">ancient Greece</a>, <b>medism</b> (<a href=\"/wiki/Greek_language\" title=\"Greek language\">Greek</a>: <span lang=\"el\">\u03bc\u03b7\u03b4\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2</span>, <i>medismos</i>) was the imitation of, sympathizing with, collaboration with, or siding with <a href=\"/wiki/Achaemenid\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Achaemenid\">Persians</a>.\n</p><p>The ethnonym \"Mede\" was often used by the Greeks of the Persians although, strictly speaking, the <a href=\"/wiki/Medes\" title=\"Medes\">Medes</a> were a different <a href=\"/wiki/Iranian_people\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Iranian people\">Iranian people</a>, subject to the Persians.  It was not until the 470s that the Greeks began to refer to \"Persians\", with <a href=\"/wiki/Aeschylus\" title=\"Aeschylus\">Aeschylus</a>' play <i>The Persians</i> in 472 being an early example of this.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Medism was considered a faux pas, even a crime, in many ancient <a href=\"/wiki/Greek_city-states\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Greek city-states\">Greek city-states</a>.  However, it does not seem to have been specifically criminalised.  For instance, in Athens suspected Medisers were charged with treason.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  The evidence suggests that this was true of other Greek <a href=\"/wiki/Polis\" title=\"Polis\">city-states</a> too: in Teos, for instance, a law from the classical period provided that anyone who betrayed the city should be punished by death, but failed to distinguish betrayal to the Persians from betrayal to any other group.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Themistocles\" title=\"Themistocles\">Themistocles</a> the Athenian was <a href=\"/wiki/Ostracism\" title=\"Ostracism\">ostracized</a> for medism. <a href=\"/wiki/Pausanias_(general)\" title=\"Pausanias (general)\">Pausanias</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Lacedaemon\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Lacedaemon\">Lacedaemonian</a> <i><a href=\"/wiki/Hegemon\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Hegemon\">hegemon</a></i> of the Hellenic League in the <a href=\"/wiki/Battle_of_Plataea\" title=\"Battle of Plataea\">Battle of Plataea</a>, was accused of medism by other member states, an accusation which allowed Athens to seize control of the league. <a href=\"/wiki/Herodotus\" title=\"Herodotus\">Herodotus</a> mentions the so-called \"state medism\" of <a href=\"/wiki/Aegina\" title=\"Aegina\">Aegina</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Thessaly\" title=\"Thessaly\">Thessaly</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Argos\" title=\"Argos\">Argos</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Thebes,_Greece\" title=\"Thebes, Greece\">Thebes</a>, and other <a href=\"/wiki/Boeotians\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Boeotians\">Boeotians</a>. Astute politicians in Athens often exploited popular feelings against medism as a means to their own advancement, which once led to a feud between the poets <a href=\"/wiki/Timocreon\" title=\"Timocreon\">Timocreon of Rhodes</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Simonides_of_Ceos\" title=\"Simonides of Ceos\">Simonides of Ceos</a> in support of and against Themistocles, respectively.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Medism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Graf, David F. (1984). \"Medism: The Origin and Significance of the Term\". <i>Journal of Hellenic Studies</i>. <b>104</b>: 18\u201319.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+Hellenic+Studies&amp;rft.atitle=Medism%3A+The+Origin+and+Significance+of+the+Term&amp;rft.volume=104&amp;rft.pages=18-19&amp;rft.date=1984&amp;rft.aulast=Graf&amp;rft.aufirst=David+F.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMedism\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Graf, David F. (1984). \"Medism: The Origin and Significance of the Term\". <i>Journal of Hellenic Studies</i>. <b>104</b>: 15\u201316.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+Hellenic+Studies&amp;rft.atitle=Medism%3A+The+Origin+and+Significance+of+the+Term&amp;rft.volume=104&amp;rft.pages=15-16&amp;rft.date=1984&amp;rft.aulast=Graf&amp;rft.aufirst=David+F.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMedism\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Graf, David F. (1984). \"Medism: The Origin and Significance of the Term\". <i>Journal of Hellenic Studies</i>. <b>104</b>: 16.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+Hellenic+Studies&amp;rft.atitle=Medism%3A+The+Origin+and+Significance+of+the+Term&amp;rft.volume=104&amp;rft.pages=16&amp;rft.date=1984&amp;rft.aulast=Graf&amp;rft.aufirst=David+F.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMedism\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Rachel M. McMullin, 'Aspects of Medizing: Themistocles, Simonides and Timocreon of Rhodes', <i>The Classical Journal</i> Vol. 97, No. 1 (Oct.-Nov. 2001), page 55</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Medism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Medism: Greek collaboration with Achaemenid Persia  by David Frank Graf</li>\n<li>Medism in the Sixth and Fifth Centuries B.C. by Helen Harriet Thompson</li>\n<li>\u201cThe Medism of Thessaly,\u201d  Henry Dickinson Westlake</li></ul>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Acropolis_of_Athens_01361.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/Acropolis_of_Athens_01361.JPG/40px-Acropolis_of_Athens_01361.JPG\" width=\"40\" height=\"24\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/Acropolis_of_Athens_01361.JPG/60px-Acropolis_of_Athens_01361.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/Acropolis_of_Athens_01361.JPG/80px-Acropolis_of_Athens_01361.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"1740\" data-file-height=\"1062\" /></a></td><td><i>This <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Greece\" title=\"Ancient Greece\">Ancient Greece</a>&#160;related article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub<